<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-059-053 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 303 175</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 16 1991 n338 p94(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting pumped up. (information technology in the chemicals andfuels industries) (part of a special section on the biggest andbest users of information technology) (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Soat, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The chemicals and fuels industries are investing heavily inleading-edge technology.andP;  A large part of that investment involvesinformation technology (IT) used to enhance exploration efforts.andO;Three-dimensional seismic survey techniques involve placing sonicdevices underground to develop a 3-D map from 5 trillion to 10trillion characters of data.andP;  Proprietary software interprets 3-Dseismic data from computer-aided exploration (CAEX) technology onUnix workstations that produce topographic models that pinpointoil sources and recommend the best methods of drilling.andP;  ThePetrotechnical Open Software Corp (POSC) is a consortia working todevelop data modeling and application programming interfaces(APIs) for oil industry computer systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information resources managementChemical industryOil industryInformation technologyInformation services.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Top chemical and fuel companies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>